A deeper look at sudo: the sudoers file and vee-sudo.

Sudo's behaviour is configured in the sudoers file under slash e-t-c, along with any drop-in files placed in the sudoers dot d directory. The syntax is its own little language. And there is one rule you must never break: never edit the sudoers file directly. Always use the vee-sudo command, which checks the syntax before saving. A single mistake in this file can lock you out of administration entirely, and vee-sudo is the guard against that.

A sudoers rule has four parts, which you can read as: who, where, as whom, and what. The who is a username, or a group name marked with a percent sign. The where is which machines the rule applies to, which only matters when one sudoers file is shared across many hosts, so it is usually just everywhere. The as-whom, in parentheses, is the identity sudo is allowed to switch to, defaulting to root. And the what is the list of commands they are permitted to run, given by full path, or the keyword for any command.

So a typical rule lets members of the sudo group run any command as root. A more careful rule might let one person restart a single service, and only that, without even prompting for a password, by adding the no-password keyword before the command path. That kind of narrow grant is exactly what sudo is good at. The preferred way to add your own rules is a drop-in file under sudoers dot d, edited through vee-sudo, which keeps your customisations separate from the distribution's main file that package updates may overwrite. And whenever sudo seems not to be working, your first move is to run sudo dash l, which lists precisely what you are allowed to do.
